snippet.textDisplay: its always worth a shot to remove the sensor and clean it with either some sensitive electronics cleaner or even battery terminal cleaner depending on the amount of corrosion. if the tanks have had water in them while it was siting the sensor might just be corroded. check it out and see! hope it works out for you. and just so you guys know do not leave the tanks full of air. the compressor squeezes the moisture out of the air and that water winds up in the air tanks. can cause a lot of weird valve and sensor issues. i always recommend draining the tanks at least once a week. should be a release valve on the tanks some where drain them all 2 or 3 times with the pressure full and it might fix your problem after cleaning that sensor

snippet.textDisplay: I would not use indoor paint in a camper!  You may get rain in the windows or water on the floor, or even mopping, you will come in contact with the paint.  The floor is going to get messed up while taking things apart, and now you have to cover it while painting.  I would have put some insulation under it, and the floor area may enlarge once you remove some more steel boxes and pieces in there.  Looks like a lot more gutting can be done.
snippet.textOriginal: I would not use indoor paint in a camper!  You may get rain in the windows or water on the floor, or even mopping, you will come in contact with the paint.  The floor is going to get messed up while taking things apart, and now you have to cover it while painting.  I would have put some insulation under it, and the floor area may enlarge once you remove some more steel boxes and pieces in there.  Looks like a lot more gutting can be done.
